title: A Summer Poem
author: kiera
text: the sun is shining brightly,  and for once i can be outside to enjoy it.  no one mentions the word photsynthesis,  and i do not have to explore it.  my dad has to go to work in the morning,  but i don't have to be up to annoy him.  of course,  i can if i want to.  after all,  it's summer vacation,   no more alarm clocks,  no more cold showers,  no more gobbling down breakfast,  no more packing my lunch,  just laughing and playing for hours.   i don't have to wear itchy uniforms,  i get to wear whatever i want.  no more untied shoes,  flip-flops instead,  that slip right on and right off.   it's summer,  it's bliss,  it's a dream come true.  and i still can't really believe it.  i'm free,  no more school. . .  but then comes september.

title: Swinging
author: kiera
text: she slid into the cherry red swing,  her friend beside her,  she began to sing.  she kicked off her sandals,  and took off her hat,  and she was in the air,  just like that.   higher and higher she went,  every moment was spent trying to get higher,  trying to touch the clouds,  for she believed she could fly.   and when it was over?  and when it was done? when she was through,  and had her fun? she put on her hat,  she slipped into her shoes,  and the girl and her friend walked away.   no more singing,  and no more swinging,  much to their great sorrow.  they had to go home and eat their dinner- at least until tomorrow.

title: Fallen to the Past
author: laura
text: one night,  a night without a sound,  nor,  me or he could see.  wewent to the window,  looked out of it,  we saw that the night had no light.  there was nothing in our sight.  as he,  we,  and of course i,  went down and down.   soon a frown -  soon a frown came upon our faces.  the hallway full of silence we noticed that under us the ground was moist.  we went along farther down the hall.  tall places where we wanted to crawl; crawl to safety.  we looked at a well,  so dirty and so -  unfortunately,  we fell into it.  with all fo the black,  and the cracks,  what if we'de fallen down a crack,  what if -  what if we'de fallen to the past! we have! we landed on an old graveyard.  terror; terror; where we were there.   i soon awoke by day's sunlight,  i looked out the window where i saw the light. . .  light so bright.   a dream? wondered i.  looking at a doll,  i saw her eye.  that was no dream!  said i with fright.  i looked down the hall,  but saw no well.  i looked above and saw that i had fallen into a well,  to the past,  was there no way back?

title: Power of Prayer
author: lauren
text: ''well,  i'm having a baby. '' mommy said with a big smile.  ''but it's not coming right away.  we'll have to wait a while. ''  i was overjoyed at the news i had died and gone to heaven.  i'd help take care of that baby even if i was only seven. . .   the nine months passed so slowly i was about ready to burst.  but when my mom was ready,  we called the hospital,  as rehearsed. . .   we drove her down to that hospital my father severely speeded.  but none of us could care at all because the hospital was needed!  i waited in the waiting room.  my dad was with my mother.  hopefully,  the baby would come soon and i'd have a sister or brother. . .   mom and dad called me in to their room.  mom had tears in each eye.  they said the baby had some heart problems and that he was going to die.   i didn't cry,  i didn't scream i had no emotions that day.  but i did do one thing. . .  i got down on my knees to pray.   dear god,  wherever you are,  please don't let my brother die.  i need him here with me on earth.  with that,  i began to cry.   i looked in the little incubator there my brother was,  so small. . .  hooked up to tubes and big machines he was barely living at all.   the next day i woke up with a start.  and went to see the baby.  i was hoping he was doing ok.  the anxiety was driving me crazy.   mom almost cried when she saw me.  she said it was a miracle alone.  my baby brother was doing fine and would be able to go home.   so now i never doubt my god i know he's always there my brother is living proof of the immense power or prayer.

title: Glacier National Park: A Place of Beauty
author: lauren
text: baby owls learning how to fly,  against a backdrop of clear,  blue sky.  young mountain goats stay by their mother's side,  and underneath the snow,  chipmunks hide!  slowly,  the tiny flowers start to sprout filling the park  with color! the rocky mountains seem to touch the sky - capped with pure,  white snow.   it's a place home to so much beauty,  even bear cubs in the dens! nothing but your eyes can capture the scenery,  no camera,  video,  or lens.   in six or seven years,  the glaciers could be gone.  no more birds,  plants,  or tiny deer fawns.  if we take away this place that these creatures call home,  the mountain goats will no longer roam.  and the eagles will not get to fly as they dare to soar across the sky.   the future of the park is all in your hands,  and we need to start helping the planet today.  do your part and save this place where the chipmunks hide and the bear cubs lay.   you,  too,  can help!

title: The Fairy Inn
author: leela
text: inside an oak,  within a hollow,  there is a place where none can follow.  behind a curtain of spider thread so thin,  glowing,  lies the fairy inn.   a happy place where small folk dwell,   where candles are lit and all is well,  elves and pixies,  nymphs so fair,  gather here,  their secret lair,   away from prying mortal eyes,  they let loose their happy cries,  and sing to goodwill henceforth,  from here in the west up to the north.   nectar whisky and petal beer,  happy drinks and happy cheer,  a place where all do want to go,  but none except the fairies know.   you cannot find a place as fine,  no ringing of bells so divine,  no taste of drinks as sweet as this,  it is truly a place of bliss.   inside an oak,  within a hollow,  there is a place where none can follow.  behind a curtain of spider thread so thin,  that,  my dear,  is the fairy inn.

title: Unstoppable
author: mackenzie
